<h2>There is no such thing as the backlog</h2>

<p>Three different queues are routinely collapsed into one word. They are different sizes,
they are counted differently, and they have been moving in opposite directions.</p>

<div class="scroll-x">
<table>
  <caption>Three separate queues</caption>
  <thead><tr><th scope="col">Queue</th><th scope="col">Latest</th><th scope="col">Direction</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><th scope="row">Awaiting a first decision</th><td>{% figure "asylum/asylum-backlog-people-awaiting-an-initial-decision" %} people, 31 March 2026</td><td>Down 55% on the year, and 72% below the June 2023 peak</td></tr>
    <tr><th scope="row">Awaiting an appeal</th><td>{% figure "asylum/asylum-appeals-backlog" %} cases, 31 March 2026</td><td>A record high, up from about 51,000 a year earlier</td></tr>
    <tr><th scope="row">Total casework in progress</th><td>{% figure "asylum/total-asylum-cases-in-the-casework-system" %} cases, June 2024</td><td><strong>Not current.</strong> The breakdown was suspended and no later complete figure exists</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

<p>Someone saying "the backlog has halved" and someone saying "the backlog is at a record
high" can both be right, about different queues. Fewer than 7,000 appeals are decided per
quarter, and the mean age of an asylum appeal at conclusion is 67 weeks.</p>

<h2>Support and accommodation</h2>

<p>{% figure "asylum/people-in-receipt-of-asylum-support" %} people were receiving asylum
support at 31 March 2026. Support means accommodation, subsistence payments, or both. Of
those,
{% figure "asylum/people-in-asylum-hotel-accommodation" %} were in hotels, around 21%.</p>

<p>This is a stock, counted on one day. It includes people at every stage of the system, some
waiting since well before the current year, and it is not a count of arrivals. See the full
check on
<a href="/common-claims/everyone-in-asylum-accommodation-arrived-recently/">whether everyone
in asylum accommodation arrived recently</a>. The figure excludes unaccompanied
asylum-seeking children, who are supported by
local authorities and counted separately.</p>

<h2>Small boats are a route, not the system</h2>

<p>{% figure "asylum/small-boat-arrivals-year-ending-march-2026" %} people were detected arriving by
small boat in the year ending March 2026, against
{% figure "asylum/asylum-applications" %} people claiming asylum over the same period.</p>

<p>Most people arriving this way do claim asylum, so the categories overlap heavily, but
they are not the same category, and the figure is published on three different bases at once
(calendar year, year ending, and year to date) which give three different numbers for what
sounds like one thing. Route of arrival also does not determine the outcome of a claim.</p>

